FLEXBOX:-
It is Flexible Box Layout Flexbox and is a layout model for arranging items (horizontally or vertically) within a container, in a flexible and responsive way.
A flexbox always consists of:
A Flex Container - The parent (container) element, where the display property is set to flex or inline-flex. For eg, dispaly: flex;
One or more Flex Items - The direct children of the flex container automatically becomes flex item


BOX MODEL:-
# Every box model consits of 4 parts content, padding, border and margin.
 Content is the text and the elements we write on the page.
 Padding is the space between the content and the border.
 Border seperates the marging and the padding and content.
 Margin is the outermost space outised the border.

BORDER:-
# Every element will always be having a border or a boundary around it.
# For a border to work it shoud be asisgne three values:-
 border-style: {values are ridge, solid, doted}
 border-width:{can have any values like 5px;}
 border-colour:{can have any values like black, red etc}
# The value of border-style should always be present for a border to act.
# To reduce the spacing of the 3 values, we can write these 3 inot a single line:-
 border: 2px solid blue;
# padding has many values like:-
 padding-top, padding-bottom, padding-right, padding-left.
 If we write like this : padding: 20 px 20px; it means bottom and top 20px and left and right 10px.
# Width and height:-
Total width=width+padding-left+padding-right
Total helight=height+padding-bottom+padding-top
Even though we've given the correct measurement for height and width this will be the total width and height. Hence to get the full control over the siszing we'll do the folowing:-

* Asterisk is called the universal selector to globally define the styles or properties we can use this.
* {
box-sizing: border-box;
}
And now the size of the elements will be as specified itself and will not change.

# There are 2 types of elements:-
 INLINE ELEMENTS:- An inline element does not start on a new line. It only takes up as much width as necessary.

 BLOCK ELEMENTS:- A block-level element always starts on a new line, and the browsers automatically add some space (a margin) before and after the element. It always takes up the full width available (stretches out to the left and right as far as it can).
 Two commonly used block elements are: <p> and <div>.

FLEX ITEMS:-
# When the parent element is flex then all the elements which are block level elements will move to the inline forma and be visible itn the smae line.
# display - Must be set to flex or inline-flex   {It displays the elements in the the same line}
# justify-content - Aligns the flex items when they do not use all available space on the main-axis (horizontally). i. e; it will give equal spacing and align the items.
 For the justify content to work the property display: flex should be present.
{The values are left|right|flex-start|flex-end|center|space-between|space-around|space-evenly|initial|inherit; }
flex-start : 	Default value. Items are positioned at the beginning of the container	
flex-end : 	Items are positioned at the end of the container	
center	: Items are positioned in the center of the container	
space-between : 	Items will have space between them	equally and there will be no space before and after the elements.
space-around : 	Items will have space before, between, and after them	
space-evenly	 : Items will have equal space around them	, not like space between everywhere the space will be equal in between, at the start and in end.
initial : 	Sets this property to its default value. 
inherit	 : Inherits this property from its parent element.
# align-items:  property is used to align the flex items vertically (on the cross-axis).align-items - Aligns the flex items when they do not use all available space on the cross-axis (vertically)
 The values are:-
normal:	Default. Behaves like 'stretch' for flexbox and grid items, or 'start' for grid items with a defined block size.	
stretch:	Items are stretched to fit the container	
center:	Items are positioned at the center of the container	both vertically and horizontally.
flex-start:	Items are positioned at the beginning of the container	
flex-end:	Items are positioned at the end of the container	
start:	Items are positioned at the top of the container.
end:	Items are positioned at the end or bottom of the their individual grid cells, in the block direction	
baseline	Items are positioned at the baseline of the container	
initial	Sets this property to its default value. Read about initial	
inherit	Inherits this property from its parent element. Read about inherit
# flex-wrap - Each and every time we use flex, we should laways write the line flex-wrap:wrap; so that the elements get the size that is speciifed. Specifies whether the flex items should wrap or not, i.e; if there is not enough room for them on one flex line. {Values are nowrap(default), wrap, wrap-reverse}
 nowrap: default one displays the items in one flex line itself.
 wrap: this will wrap if necessary. i.e; if ther is no space for the next elements in the screen it moves it to the nest line and continues.
 wrap-reverse: This will wrap the items if necessary but in the reverse direction i.e; it moves the element in the upward direction.
 initial:	Sets this property to its default value. 
 inherit:	Inherits this property from its parent element.
